Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: My motivation stems from the growing need to bridge the gap between model uncertainty and human interpretability in AI-assisted decision-making, particularly in high-stakes domains like medical imaging or autonomous systems where segmentation tasks are critical. While existing methods quantify uncertainty via entropy or Bayesian dropout, they often fail to translate this into actionable, user-centric visualizations. Inspired by Paper 3’s HEAR system—which communicates uncertainty to prevent misguidance—and Paper 2’s emphasis on explaining *why* uncertainty arises, I propose a novel framework that goes beyond passive visualization: enabling users to actively *steer* segmentation outcomes through intent-conditioned confidence regions. Unlike static uncertainty maps, my idea introduces dynamic, interactive predictive regions that adapt not only to model confidence but also to user-specified levels of risk tolerance and semantic intent (e.g., “be conservative around tumors” or “prioritize sensitivity for small lesions”). This integrates ordinal likelihood hierarchies—akin to Paper 1’s non-probabilistic uncertainty stratification—but applies them spatially and semantically within segmentation outputs. The key innovation lies in treating uncertainty not as a post-hoc diagnostic, but as a first-class control interface. By conditioning the expansion/contraction of predictive regions on both data-driven uncertainty and user intent, we enable a bidirectional dialogue between human and model. This differs from prior work by unifying three dimensions: (1) uncertainty quantification, (2) intent-based modulation, and (3) real-time visual feedback—all within a single interactive framework. It moves beyond explanation toward *collaborative refinement*, allowing users to explore trade-offs between precision and recall under varying confidence thresholds, guided by interpretable uncertainty boundaries.

